The descriptions of Sisos of earth and water in the new exhibition.
"People Swimming in the Swimming Pool" from 2022 is a work of art by Vicente Siso, which will be exhibited starting January 13 in the "Tierra del Sol" gallery (photo provided by Vicente Siso)
"Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" - this is the title of the exhibition at the new location of the "Tierra del Sol" gallery in West Hollywood. Siso has been participating as an artist in the Studio Arts Program since 2012 and is now showing his first solo exhibition. Siso was born in Madrid in 1962 and grew up in Venezuela, Trinidad, and Miami. He later moved with his family to Southern California.
In numerous series of landscapes, portraits, and still lifes in acrylic, pastel, charcoal, or watercolor, Siso demonstrates his excellent skill. Inspired by family portraits, his own reference photographs, and through memories, his colorful compositions prove the entire spectrum of his interests and his abilities in different mediums. His tropical landscapes and works of water show the places of his past in detailed patterns. People are also integrated to create a meaningful connection between culture, memory, and nature. Siso titles his artworks with a mixture of Spanish and English - a sign of the celebrated and so important complexities of his life in Los Angeles County. "Vicente Siso: Memories of the Land and Water" opens on Saturday, January 13th with a reception from 6:00 PM to 8:00 PM. The exhibition will be on display until Sunday, March 3rd.
Gallery "Tierra del Sol", 7414 Santa Monica Blvd. Further information can be found at tierradelsolgallery.org.
Adapt the old, integrate the new and thus solve problems.
At the district level, we only need to look at Sydney's Central Business District: an originally non-urbanized landscape first transformed into a city with two-story buildings with a maximum height of 46 meters, and then into today's city with impressive towers. On a much smaller scale, this can happen in Sydney's city centers around central transport hubs. Even central city districts must continue to develop with a trend towards affordable living space with buildings that are still surpassed by greenery in crucial areas. Naturally, this newly created living space must be convincing in terms of design and greenery, landscape design, and parks must be integrated alongside other essential infrastructure.
Our planning system must also adapt, so that those responsible in the central district councils of the city, who are rather critical of changes, do not have the sole power over the future formation of their neighborhoods. One possibility could be the establishment of an independent decision-making office, which advocates for high-quality concepts that invariably remain below the height of the existing buildings and provide space for families, large loggias and communal gardens - and visually, the whole thing must also be convincing. This could be a lesson for the current NSW government architect, in which context the elaborated decree must be meticulously adhered to.
In the last 10 years, our lives have changed through technology. Many work from home and Sydney has gained an impressive network of underground railways and city trains. Online shopping has changed our way of buying and thanks to smartphones, friends and families can maintain contact more easily. Precisely such adaptations from one system to another are also possible in our manufacturing environments. The main focus of planning must therefore be on adaptive new use, instead of on the old favored conservation.
Chris Johnson was NSW Government Architect from 1995 to 2005 and Principal Director of the NSW Planning Department from 2005 to 2009. From 2011 to 2019, he was CEO of Urban Taskforce Australia.
A final postulate for the equality of women.
Last year, the World Economic Forum predicted that it would take five generations to achieve gender equality in every country. Now the World Bank wants to significantly shorten this timeframe.
The international economic institution is to introduce a strategy with which the economic rights and opportunities for girls and women are to be clearly promoted by the year 2030. The plan focuses on improving inclusion and resilience through access to finance, technological innovation, and changes in public policies and laws.
"The latest research has shown that social norms as well as ways of thinking can change and that inclusion, for example of men and boys, can lead to them supporting gender equality," it says in the draft consultation of the plan. "Positive results for equality can be accelerated and scaled up if it is better understood... how social norms and mentalities influence daily expectations, priorities, and practices."
Changes in thinking are difficult to quantify – in comparison with bank loans for women in the countryside or school registrations for girls. Nevertheless, numerous indications suggest that the integration of women can move mountains. In Iran, for example, women have become the greatest threat to the Islamic government for over 40 years: they have refused to abide by laws that force them to cover their hair. In a few of the 130 countries with minimum quotas for female representation in government, for example in India, male resistance against women's right to vote and political activity has decreased.
In some rural communities in Africa, civil society organizations have replaced an extremely harmful initiation rite with health education. One of these programs helped Kamanda Timayio, traditional leader of the Maasai Maparasha community in Kenya, to change his attitude towards female genital mutilation. He told Le Monde that he had "overcome his ignorance" and that he would give up the practice.
The World Bank cites further examples. From 1970 to 2022, the literacy rate of women in Bangladesh quadrupled and women's labor force participation doubled. The country's gross domestic product more than tripled. The change developed its own dynamic. The employment of women as paid teachers and health workers in the communities themselves created trust "and made the mobility and professional activity of women more socially acceptable."
The bank's plan targets the norms and institutions where a generational change might still be missing. It took more than two decades in Rwanda for the country to establish itself as a model for land reform, through which the economic empowerment of women was promoted. "It helps no one if women are held back," said Rwandan President Paul Kagame when he proclaimed a land reform in 2015. "We must change the way of thinking, not just the laws."
The World Bank hopes to be able to disseminate this message.
Germanische Bauern und Lokführer schüchtern germanische Unternehmer ein.
In Germany, where employees and employers run many businesses together, large strikes are unusual. There has practically never been a large wave of strikes. But at the moment, the "country of co-determination" is facing a week of strikes, in which not only angry farmers will block the roads with tractors for eight days, but where railway workers will also strike for three days in a row. And to top it all off, a doctors' strike is also imminent, and doctors' practices had already closed between Christmas and New Year. This "pitchfork mob," as some call it, will put Germany's harmonious labor relations to the test in the coming year.
The protests were apparently triggered by the government's decision to cut diesel subsidies for agriculture and reduce tax breaks for agricultural motor vehicles. These measures were the last straw for the farmers. They also mobilised other disgruntled employees who were already suffering under the burden of inflation, economic stagnation and the imposed austerity measures. On January 9, German railway freight and passenger train drivers began a strike over working hours and pay.
To reduce tensions with the farmers, the government has declared itself ready for a phased reduction of diesel subsidies over the next three years. The tax exemption for motor vehicles should also be maintained. The farmers rejected the concessions as insufficient. On January 4, Economy Minister Robert Habeck wanted to leave the ferry after his return from family vacation - but an angry group of protesters tried to prevent him from doing so. If the train drivers also prove to be so unimpressed, this could become expensive for the German economy, estimates the Institute for Economic Research IW Köln. The train strike could cost the economy 100 million euros every day if production has to be interrupted. The automotive, chemical, and steel industries, Germany's largest economic sectors, are particularly dependent on rail freight traffic.
The mood among employees is becoming increasingly irritable. "Calls for revolution fantasies are circulating," Habeck warned. The far-right party Alternative for Germany is doing its utmost to strengthen the protests. In Dresden, the Freie Sachsen, another far-right extremist party, infiltrated the farmers' protests and called for "the elimination of the Ampel (traffic light coalition)".
Thomas Puls from IW Köln fears that the protests could damage Germany's reputation as an economic location. Local entrepreneurs already fear a German version of the yellow vest protests in France in 2018, which ended with demonstrators setting cars on fire on the Champs-Élysées and the police using tear gas. Jochen Kopelke, federal chairman of the police union, warned in an interview with Tagesspiegel: "The farmers' protests are probably just the beginning of a gigantic wave of protests that will come this year." Germany was the only one of the major economic regions that shrank in 2023, and the year ended on a particularly bitter note: with an unexpected decline in economic confidence in December. This year could become even more difficult.
Brewers are outraged by the wine producers' exemption from the regulations on avoiding impurities.
In connection with the EU debate on regulations for waste avoidance, breweries argue that they are disadvantaged by exceptions for winemakers regarding reuse quotas and deposit-return systems. One of the leaders of the European wine industry association, however, believes that brewers "should mind their own business."
European breweries warn that it is unfair and possibly illegal to allow exceptions from reuse quotas, as well as from deposit-return systems for wine - but not for beer. Meanwhile, legislators are in the final round of discussions on a new law that should lead to a change in the increasing mountains of packaging waste in the EU.
The environment ministers stipulated a negotiating mandate of the European Council regarding the packaging and packaging waste regulations proposed before Christmas and cleared the way for immediate political discussions pending with the European Parliament, which are already ongoing at the professional level.
"Our position is clear," wrote the central association of European brewers, Brewers of Europe, to the delegates of the European Parliament and the leaders of the government negotiations (January 10). "If the proposals and regulations of the packaging and packaging waste directive apply to beer, then there is a legal obligation to apply it to all categories of alcoholic beverages."
At the supreme meeting of ministers on December 18, an exception was decided for the requirements for winemakers, who must offer 10% of their products in reusable and refillable containers by the end of the decade. By 2040, this share should grow to 40%. This exception should also apply to the requirement that wine be exempt from the deposit-return system. This requirement is also being introduced by the European Parliament and should be introduced as part of the proposal by the year 2029.
The Czech minister and the Belgian minister immediately expressed their reservations at the supreme meeting on December 18 regarding the unequal treatment of citizens, but agreed. Belgium, which now holds the rotating presidency of the EU Council and should therefore remain neutral in the negotiations between the governments, hopes that an agreement with the parliament will be reached by the beginning of March.
Ignacio Sánchez Recarte, Secretary General of the European Wine Industry Association, the Comité Européen des Entreprises Vin, which represents approx. 7,000 winegrowers throughout Europe, says no to the doubts of beer producers. He told Euronews that a market dominated by multinational brewery conglomerates cannot be compared to an industry that consists almost exclusively of small local producers.
More than 99% of the indigenous wine industry consists of very small to medium-sized businesses, said Sánchez Recarte. He also questioned the validity of the legal arguments that had been put forward by the breweries. In his opinion, his organization has focused on providing "relevant and adequate" information to the decision-makers in their own industry.
"It is not my role to evaluate whether the beer industry should have this or that goal, because that depends on concrete attributes of their own industry," said Sánchez Recarte. "Therefore, brewers should take care of their own business and concentrate on their own duties."
Brewers of Europe has shared a short legal analysis with Euronews, which had been sent by the association last year to the European Commission. In it, it argued that wine and beer are competing products that are "at least partially mutually replaceable," and that rules favoring one industry over another distort the market.
Simon Spillane, the head of lobbying operations, said that brewers are "already at the forefront" in sustainable packaging. He pointed out reusable containers that can be reused about 165 times before they are sorted and recycled after 30 years. They support reuse and recycling systems that have already been introduced in many countries.
"That's why we are advocating for an ambitious packaging and packaging waste regulation. But we also need the same conditions in packaging legislation, according to which beer and other alcoholic beverages are treated according to the same rules. Every industry should contribute in the same way to achieve the goals and support the collection systems," said Spillane. "Any other starting point means an economic disadvantage for brewers."
Biden administration lets economic criminals get away
Tim Whitehouse, former attorney for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and executive director of Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility, praised the Biden administration's recent improvements in environmental enforcement, but also conceded that such efforts face strong opposition. "It takes years of reliable funding and political support to build a good enforcement program," he told me. "Instability in Congress not only demoralizes EPA staff, but also jeopardizes their ability to think strategically long-term."
The problems of the EPA are not exactly identical, but comparable to those of the Ministry of Justice. The Environment and Natural Resources Division (ENRD) of the latter deals with environmental crime. Uhlmann, the Deputy Minister for Implementation Issues, was, before he came to the EPA, head of the environmental crime sector from 1990 to 2007. The EPA sends its most difficult civil and criminal cases to the ENRD, which, as a relatively poorly funded body, often relies on others to decide which battles should be fought. In the 2022 fiscal year, the EPA referred fewer cases (88) to the Ministry of Justice than at any other time since 2000 and concluded the fewest civil proceedings since then. As noted in the ecological integrity project, the EPA even under Trump concluded an average of 94 civil proceedings and referred 106 cases per year to the Ministry of Justice.
The general procedure of the Ministry of Justice in cases of economic crime has been intensively monitored by supporters. Observers have praised a few steps that the ministry has taken under Merrick Garland as Minister of Justice - such as, for example, the establishment of a database for economic crime. However, Biden's Ministry of Justice has also relied heavily on major loss regulations, with which companies suspend or can avoid criminal proceedings, and to encourage entrepreneurs to report individual employees to avoid extensive complaints. Kenneth Polite Jr., former acting Minister of Justice in the criminal division, revised the division's implementation guidelines for companies to restrict criminal prosecutions.
Shutdown debate causes conflict among Republicans
Conservative opponents of spending in the House of Representatives today went against the party leadership and caused a series of votes to fail. With this, they protested against the latest budget agreement by Speaker Mike Johnson with the Democrats, which in their opinion does not foresee enough spending cuts.
But the Louisiana Republican can't get around the issue, as the deadline for the deliberation of four of the twelve annual economic plans expires on January 19. Johnson has publicly declared that he will not support a transitional law, which he describes as a "Continuing Resolution" for the extension of the deadline for these four draft laws to February 2, which applies to the remaining eight economic plans.
In view of the fact that this deadline is only nine days away, the Republican Senate Minority Leader, Mitch McConnell, announced that Congress must pass a "Continuing Resolution" to keep the government running. With this, Johnson risks breaking a promise with which he had wanted to calm especially the right wing of his party. Such a maneuver would most likely result in a furious ideological debate about the role of Republicans in spending cuts, so that a partial government shutdown or Johnson's dismissal could occur.
Congressman Matt Rosendale of Montana told Newsweek: "I have been very clear that 'Continuing Resolutions' are not the appropriate way to fund our government, because the Budget Act of 1974 provides for the approval of 12 appropriations bills. We have had plenty of time for that, and if the leadership does not order the committee to do its homework and let the congressmen vote on it, then that is the reason for the mess."
The Speaker of the House of Representatives, Mike Johnson, at the U.S. Capitol on December 12, 2023 in Washington, D.C. Johnson is confronted with a revolutionary Republican faction that is unable to reach an agreement on the level of economic spending. Photo: Kevin Dietsch/Getty Images
Rosendale, who belongs to the far-right Freedom Caucus, was one of those who caused the vote to fail on Wednesday. According to him, the total amount in Johnson's proposal is too high and he does not see it as sufficient to lower the state's debt of 34 trillion dollars.
Rosedale also belonged to those 71 Republicans who opposed the Fiscal Responsibility Act: the law that had been negotiated between the Democrats and former Speaker Kevin McCarthy regarding fiscal responsibility, where general conditions had been stipulated for Johnson's last negotiations with the head of the Democrats in the Senate, Charles Schumer.
While Johnson praised his agreement, because with it expenses in the amount of an estimated 16 billion dollars would be saved, the Freedom Caucus is of the opinion, however, that he could have gotten even more out. Moderate Republicans, who had supported McCarthy's agreement, are of the idea that this stance is unrealistic and contrary to the goal of the Republicans, to force Congress to deliberate the twelve spending bills individually and not to summarize them as in past years as a so-called omnibus procedure in a single vote.
"New year, same idiotic behaviour from a few," declared Republican delegate Mike Lawler from New York to Newsweek. "Because there will be no omnibus procedure, every bill must be discussed and negotiated separately. Apparently, this will probably take more time. And I am not for a shutdown - so I also have no problem with a short-term 'Continuing Resolution' so that this process can be completed."
It was the first time since 1996 that Congress deliberated all twelve draft laws by hand. According to Lawler, the delayed deliberation of the four draft laws is to ensure that the process can proceed in an orderly manner. If Congress does not manage to deliberate the twelve draft laws by December, the Fiscal Responsibility Act would be used to cut the economy by one percent on judicial expenses in the defense and non-defense sectors.
The congressional delegate Thomas Massie from Kentucky - certainly one of the most outspoken opponents of spending in the Republican party - was not among those who protested against the vote on Wednesday. He did, however, declare that a one-year "Continuing Resolution" with the consequence of a one percent spending cut would be the most practical way to keep the government running and at the same time end the continuous brinkmanship.
The way with the greatest responsibility to achieve the spending cuts, according to Massie, would be the approval of all twelve draft laws. Many Republicans, however, are only hesitantly in favor of a shutdown and thus risk a cut of a percentage of defense spending. The urgency with which the draft laws must be deliberated could thus lead to a sufficient number of Republicans joining the Democrats to extend the deadline for the first four draft laws and to reach an agreement on the financing of government work, even if this would mean angering a few of the hardliners on the right wing for Johnson.
"It (the one percent cut) should serve as motivation and a means of pressure to pass the twelve draft laws," Massie declared to Newsweek. "I think we could first decide on a 'Continuing Resolution' for one year, then present our arguments, and if we face this small obstacle, I hope everyone will be motivated to act reasonably. That's how I would do it."
The supervisory authority approves new Bitcoin ETFs - a decisive moment for cryptocurrency.
The US stock exchange supervisory authority Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) reluctantly cleared the way for Bitcoin exchange-traded funds (ETFs) on Wednesday. This is a digital currency long awaited by supporters and a step criticized by financial observers who are skeptical of the crypto industry.
The authority has approved ten ETFs that invest in Bitcoin, including funds from industry giants like Blackrock and Fidelity, but also from smaller financial companies.
"The fact that we have today approved the listing of the stock exchange and the trading of certain bitcoin products traded on the stock exchange does not mean that we approve of bitcoin or that we are for bitcoin," said SEC chief Gary Gensler in a statement. "Investors should, as before, be cautious in view of the numerous risks in connection with bitcoin and products whose value is linked to the crypto currency."
He added that the approval of bitcoin funds does not mean that funds or exchange-traded products (ETPs) based on other digital currencies or asset values are approved by the SEC.
"It is important that today's approval is limited to ETPs that contain a certain non-security product, namely bitcoin. With this, we are by no means signaling a readiness to allow admission standards for crypto assets. The approval also says nothing about the SEC's stance towards the status of other crypto assets within the framework of federal securities laws or about the situation of non-compliance with federal securities laws by certain participants in the crypto-asset market," said Gensler.
For years, petitions for similar funds have been rejected by the SEC. Last year, however, the US Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia ruled that the SEC's refusal to approve a Grayscale petition for the conversion of a derivative fund was illegal. This fund was to be converted into a fund that would invest directly in bitcoin. The court found the SEC's stance to be "unfounded and arbitrary."
Gensler has declared that, in view of these circumstances and those that are explained in more detail in the permit decision, he is of the opinion that the most solid path for the future exists in the permit for the quotation and trading of these spot bitcoin ETP parts.
The eagerly awaited approval was celebrated as a decisive moment for digital currencies. According to proponents, it increases access to bitcoin investments and could lead to wider acceptance of cryptocurrencies as serious financial investments. The price of bitcoin has risen explosively in recent months from around 25,000 dollars in September to over 45,000 dollars. This is partly due to the fact that many bitcoin investors believe that ETFs will create greater demand for the asset.
Opponents of the decision strongly criticised the SEC on Wednesday evening.
Dennis M. Kelleher, co-founder, president and CEO of Better Markets, announced that the permit is a "historic mistake". Through it, not only crypto leaders would be unleashed on tens of millions of investors and pensioners, but probably also the stability of the financial markets would be undermined.
Kelleher further stated, "The apparently lawless crypto industry is, due to a flurry of arrests, criminal convictions, insolvencies, lawsuits, scandals, massive losses, and millions of victims among investors and clients, at its absolute lowest point. Who would have thought that it would be supported by the SEC, by them approving it as a proven and familiar investment form. Through this, the SEC enables the mass marketing of a notoriously worthless, volatile, and fraudulent financial product to American citizens."
30% increase in complaints about the use of the Russian language in Ukraine - RT Russia and former Soviet Union
To reforest the country, the population is asked by the government to bring plants.
The number of complaints to the Ukrainian authorities about Russian-speaking individuals increased by 30% last year. The authorities in Kyiv are actively urging the population to report such cases, seemingly to "protect" the country from Russian influence.
According to information from the office of the Commissioner for the Protection of the National Language, 3,692 violations of the language law were reported in 2023. Kyiv, Kharkiv, and Odesa are "as always at the top of the number of complaints about violations. Therefore, this year it should be among the priorities of the communal authorities to strictly monitor that the language rights of citizens are upheld in all sectors of public life," said Taras Kremen, the language ombudsman in Ukraine.
Kremen also confirmed that a taxi driver from Kyiv, who had spoken Russian with his client, was fined 3,400 Hryvnia (89 dollars). The mediator drew the public's attention to the existence of a "detailed algorithm of measures, which, if exceeded, should result in information and services being provided in the national language." He urged the population to immediately submit complaints in such cases on the authorities' website.
In 2019, Ukraine passed a law that mandates the use of the Ukrainian language in all sectors of public life, including government, medicine, science, education, and media. Fines are imminent for transgressions. Since the beginning of the military conflict with Russia in 2022, Ukraine has organized a campaign for complete de-Russification, which parliamentarians view as necessary to protect against Russian influence. Local authorities have completely banned artworks, productions, books, films, songs, and instruction in the Russian language in schools and universities, and recommended that schoolchildren speak Ukrainian among themselves even during breaks.
In August of last year, a young musician was briefly arrested and forced to apologize via video message after singing songs by Soviet singer Viktor Tsoi on the streets of Lviv. The dismissal of several teachers who spoke Russian with their students also caused a public outcry.
The secretary of the National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine, Oleksiy Danilov, had previously declared that the Russian language must disappear from Ukrainian territory, because it is "an element of hostile and poisonous propaganda for the minds of the population".
Moscow is of the opinion that such laws violate the rights of the Russian-speaking population, which makes up about half of Ukraine's inhabitants. The spokeswoman for the Russian Foreign Ministry, Maria Zakharova, declared in February that Kyiv's "discriminatory campaign" against the language was becoming "increasingly indignant." In a survey conducted last September by the International Institute of Sociology in Kyiv, 45% of respondents declared linguistic discrimination as the most common form of prejudice in Ukraine.
Celeste is my favorite "small, good freeware - to large commercial game with incredibly detailed graphics" in the corruption arc, because in the original the Double Dash is an inconsistent Power-Up in a treasure chest and in the commercial game it makes me scream.
In general, I particularly like the interaction of the two games. The advantage of short stories is that you can "jump to the good part". This can be more interesting and satisfying. With long stories, the advantage is that you can give much greater emotional weight to the elements of action. Nothing happens very quickly, but in return you also get more.
The highlight of Celeste, the commercial game, is truly just the Pico-8-Game, and that has been mechanically and narratively expanded by several hours, making it much, much harder. Celeste is so proud of its little Parent Game that it constantly makes allusions, like the monument to the development "2000 M...2500 M...", the Power-Up, the banner above. You can play the original game directly on the start screen!
Celeste is neither "the good version" nor the "final version" of Pico-8, it is just another version of the same main story. As someone who loves short as well as long stories, it is really interesting and crazy to see how the connection was made so apparently.
It would have been possible to create an additional medium-length version between the two versions, which tells the same extended and impactful story, but with a shorter duration and less absurd production values. I believe that would have been my preferred variant, as an arc of emotional tension. Instead, the main arc of tension for a single player in the commercial game is only a small part of that. Above all, it wants to be a great playground for the world's most well-known physics platform, which in my opinion is still in order.
