I've only needed general anesthesia for one single operation so far. That was a "small" neurosurgical operation, where more space was made for my brain, because I was born with a malformation, due to which I developed symptoms after the birth of my children (Chiari malformation). I have never forgotten the moment I woke up and I relive it a little every time I watch medical shows, especially if a neurosurgeon appears there 😂. I've had Hospital Playlist on my list for a long time and I'm really enjoying it right now. #kdrama
My surgeon really thinks of everything. He called me the day before because it was supposed to snow, and when the treatment team took care of me as I woke up in the recovery room from the anesthesia, my surgeon noticed that I hadn't opened my eyes and that the bandage was in front of my eyes. I thought, all the more so for the operation. But it was still irritating. That was among the most frightening things I've ever done. I slept and it was already over.
I hadn't had my period, but I should have taken it out. That's why they gave me this mesh underwear, which is worn after the straw. But in the OP you are completely undressed and covered with a cloth. Sometime, before I woke up, a friendly nurse changed my underwear. Apart from births, where I was conscious and received help or as a baby, no one has ever done anything so private for me. That was also my only time in the intensive care unit. I had to go to the intensive care unit as a precautionary measure due to the type of operation.
Because of my operation, I had to recover a lot, so I watched seasons 1-3 of Grey's Anatomy. That McDreamy was a neurosurgeon helped. I paid attention to how the patient was lying, so I could imagine what would happen to me. Since my 2018 operation, there has been more about neurosurgery in Hospital Playlist than in any other doctor show since I watched Grey's Anatomy. How nice that there is art and entertainment to give our lives meaning.
