I think a lot about how millennials were the last generation who could build relationships with artists without being expected to also view them critically.
We didn't grow up in a golden age of media, with a collective memory for pop culture, which no longer exists.
They couldn't jump into things without having to think about where they came from, because at that time it wasn't so easy to ascertain that.
We didn't have to question the pedestal on which we placed them. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still new, my friends and I would order pizza every Thursday and watch the series together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, when 12 episodes come out at once and everyone watches when they feel like it and marks social media posts with "spoiler alert" or discusses it in isolated groups.
Unconsciously we long for this universal community, which used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch series like "The Office", or films like "Anchorman", in which there were so many individual lines that would be memes today.
All these sayings have been sent out and have come out of it, that most people already understand them.
Today, one can no longer even get out of the fact that everyone knows something, even if it spreads massively virally.
There's far too much and there's no possibility of fixing it. If we ever get out of this mess again?
We are not trapped in a vicious circle of always discovering new content, only to then realize that the artist is broke or a simulator.
Therefore we must hold on firmly to our nostalgia and at the same time accept that the people who created the works that pleased us can also have great flaws.
We enter into parasocial relationships with greater caution.
It is clear that it is difficult to become rich and powerful without stepping on someone's toes on the way.
Because we are losing our collective memory regarding the media, we have developed a class memory that promotes our critical thinking.
There are still some among us who raise someone onto a pedestal, only to be shocked when they then fall down.
We are in a phase of change and I am very curious how it will turn out in the end.
