It is an absolute niche problem, but if you want to build/customize small robot figures, it is really the case that you MUST build something that is made for war or killing.
Like in the noughties. There were Bionicles. These were adventurers/heroes with entire elemental powers and different personalities and hobbies and so on, but before and after there's only something like Warhammer, Gundam, Battletech where everything is meant to be a weapon, which is completely unnecessarily exposed in the accompanying media.
It's clear, these other sources SAY "war is bad", but then they still sell killing machines as figures and merchandise. So what should we do?
I think the solution is to separate between their appearance and this fictitious use, as is also done in the real world with tanks and jets, but my brain has DIFFICULTIES with that.
Even though the figures look cool, and I like how they are built and how their design reflects certain character qualities, then it says with every set: "By the way, here is your laser sword and your (at least one) pistol!"
This is probably largely because boys' toys almost always have something to do with violence, such as GI Joe and Transformers, but once all honest, we are in the present.
I'm already looking forward to seeing Berry's pacifist robot family 3D printed ;)
@user25 oh, that's the idea, in any case, as soon as I have the skills for it
An avowed anarchist, who doesn't care a bit about keeping his identity secret, gives his DNA to a biotechnology company to get a dubious overview of his "ancestry". What could possibly go wrong there?
My wife wanted this as a starting point. Without going too deep into it, but she believes that some of her apparent ancestors are not really her ancestors. I want to support her and see the effect of genetic drift using a small control sample. We know a lot about our family.
Perhaps there is one or the other in my family who has been unfaithful, but if one considers my largely poor family roots, the affairs probably happened more or less in homogeneous communities, small towns and ethnic ghettos, lol.
My grandmother left her husband for his brother, and I have a second cousin on the other side of the family who left his wife for her aunt. My family might be going in circles because of this, but it's not really getting anywhere.
And now my wife is in a bad mood, because my "extraction" went much faster than expected. I'm sorry, maybe her genome shouldn't be so easily questioned.
The results are here and - drumroll please - they fully agree with my family history. 89.9% British and Irish, most of it concentrated in the Scottish Borders region, Western Ireland, Wales and Cornwall. However, there isn't much Breton, perhaps because it's either so close to Cornwall that it can't be differentiated for me, or my Breton family part doesn't originate from there.
Because I'm around 40, I was a bit worried that there might be children I didn't know anything about. So far, only one of my cousins has abandoned his children (maybe).
Woe to you, King Louis XIV, one of your descendants is an anarchist!
Difficult woman: Now, with this DNA test, are you referring to the Scottish and Irish parts?
I, in a kilt of checkered Johnston and reading the "Elders of Ireland": No, that wouldn't fit into my life.
If it's a day off, I don't normally wear basketball shorts if I'm just wandering around.
