As an academic, one rarely has time for recreation, but during the time one is not sitting at the desk, the best ideas come to you.
Working harder, to publish more, does not always lead to better results. One must not forget to relax if one wants to become a better scientist.
So I'm recharging my batteries again:
Use both halves of the brain.
As scientists, we no longer need the analytical part of our brain. But if I use the creative part (e.g. when playing guitar, painting, etc.) and also the analytical part of my brain, it feels as if I have increased my mental capacity. Through this, I become better in both fields.
Train muscles, not just the body. 💪
Sport is not just for future triathletes or people who want to look better. Sport also improves the quality of life. Mood, atmosphere, productivity - all of that goes together. Taking a break and leaving the desk once in a while makes the time at the desk more productive again.
Permission to resume. 📺
Recharging your batteries doesn't necessarily mean you have to adopt new habits. A good film or a good book can have just as much effect as creative work and physical activity. The important thing is to become aware that it's okay to relax and do nothing. There's no room for feelings of guilt there!
I've noticed that these things help me recover. But there are many more. What isn't done to keep oneself enthusiastic about science and not get a burnout? 🤔
#academics #science #promotion #phdlife #typefully
