Okay, I put up the new birdhouse today. This is how it looks in its new spot in the garden.
But let's go back a bit. Nobody asks: "What exactly is in here?"
Above is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a fisheye lens camera and an IR-LED, which I got from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the curious shape of this plastic box is the swiveling side wall of the nesting box. I bought it like that and couldn't change it, so I had to build around it.
Since it does not provide any electrical power in the garden, this entire piece of furniture is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 cell.
I didn't photograph the cell or the charger, but here is a photo of the panel.
In the gray box, which hangs on the side of the fire box, is the battery.
Once it is charged, it has a duration of approximately 4 hours.
That's what you call a feature. This way the birds also get a bit of privacy.
At the beginning it was not clear whether the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this construction. The old access points, which I replaced last autumn, would not have been enough.
But the new ones discover this field very well.
That's almost a shame, because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and point it downwards into the garden.
Perhaps I'll do that again if I put up more nesting boxes with cameras. Especially in fields that are further away from the house, that's probably necessary.
