The development of humanity proceeds continuously. Even in difficult times, we continue to develop and adapt. In cities, there is still great prosperity, and technological progress is set in motion. With the recent discovery of Ignniat, humanity has catapulted itself to the highest peaks, but the greatest is yet to come. This newly acquired knowledge, which has been given to humanity, can only be valued as a divine work, and the gods will rejoice at our presence in heaven. The company Karascene has had Ignniat extensively examined and values the potential of this mineral very highly. And no fear: According to the examinations, no side effects or problems are to be expected during the exploitation of Ignniat. This mineral is destined for something greater.
January 14, 2543, at 10:26 PM.
A click. The same stream is repeated again and again: the day the world was devastated. My father always shut it off when he saw that I couldn't look away. His worried expression made my stomach clench. I always feel bad when this stream plays, because it awakens so many memories in me, and not very good ones. He sighs to get up and think about other things. I constantly try to cheer him up and chase away his bad mood, by giving him at least a little pleasure, but today I'm tired.
I slowly approach the door and call out to my father: "I'm going out for a bit, dinner is in the fridge." No answer. How else. Often he'll just look out for himself. I slowly close the door and sigh once more, after it has completely closed. I almost forgot to put my hand on the cold metal scanner to lock the door. If there was something that distinguished this apartment, it was its equipment with modern technology, which, however, would apply to most buildings. For a long time, no other technology had been used.
In this rainy and cold night I took my exploration walk through Paltricus, which should have been done a long time ago - a privilege reserved for those who had managed to escape the mutation through flight or pure luck. The night was lit by shining stars, which had existed for thousands of years. One feels alone in the universe. Paltricus was a beautiful city, but it felt more like a cage than a luxurious home. The city was overflowing with dwellings, houses and other habitations, most of which were several hundred meters high, thanks to Ignniat. This mineral had proven to be a boon for technology and architecture and increased our basis of life. However, the public knows little about this mineral, especially because it is subject to strict secrecy.
To free myself from my sad thoughts, I set off for a coffee at my favorite place. Many people avoid it because of rumors of a bandit who is said to be active in the area. That's what those who have been infected with the virus are called. That never bothered me - I had been incredibly lucky in my life - and the owner was a great guy. Who would ever give up a free coffee in exchange for a night's conversation?
When I entered, my discomfort was dispelled by a ringing sound and I smelled the aroma of freshly brewed coffee. Anton, the owner of the place, was as always behind the counter. The place was practically empty, except for a few people in the back. After the long walk, I approached the counter, dead tired, let myself fall onto one of the stools and sighed. I saw Anton and he brought me the usual. "Hi Lilith, long night?", his rough voice echoed through the vaults of my brain. "So-so", I replied, exhausted and getting more tired by the second.
To chase away my boredom, I tried a few sips of the coffee that was in front of me. "Are things still going badly since the story with the bandit...?" I spoke very quietly, so as not to scare away the last guests in Anton's place. He nodded, while he cleaned a mug with a cloth. This place is actually a bar, but I never came here to drink. Behind me, a murmur was heard, but the conversation between Anton and me was rather short today. With a short nod and a bit more energy than before, I left the place.
It wasn't the best idea to walk late at night through the dark streets. But still better than staying in that stuffy apartment and listening to the neighbors having sex. You heard them more often than your own music. With a short sigh, I directed my gaze back to the street in front of me. I'll probably go to Al's shop, the pawnbroker, to pass the time, looking for interesting loot. When I heard footsteps close behind me, I regretted my decision. Maybe I was worrying too much, but in these neighborhoods, it was really easy, if you let it happen, to get robbed or mugged. The neighborhoods were known for the mafia and gang crime...
Truly amusing. Only half of humanity is left and yet we don't refuse to bash each other's heads in. I started walking faster, the pawn shop was right around the corner and inside it was safe. When I stood safely in front of a brightly lit sign with the inscription "Alborn's Pawn Shop", I confirmed with a glance over my shoulder that I was no longer being pursued. With a calmer step, I entered the shop. This place was rather out of the way, because Alborn often took in mutants who were without permission in Paltricus. It was dark in the shop and Al was curiously not there. No fugitives. Nothing. Something wasn't right here.
Cautiously I went from one shelf to another in the back part of the shop, where behind a metal counter one could hear a few handfuls being quickly taken away, grumbling and low voices. I climbed into the ventilation shaft - at that moment the simplest and safest method. When I pushed myself through, I heard conversations between the men, who were strangely dressed. Then I saw Al in chains. It was clear that they would eventually catch him.
I really wanted to go to Alborn, but that was too big a number for me. I really shouldn't stick my nose into other people's business, especially not when they are looking for a fight with the state power. Nevertheless, I couldn't do otherwise. Sighing softly, I slowly pulled the cat out from under me from its fixation and let it down quietly in the room. "Psst. Al. Al!" I whispered, and when he didn't answer, I came closer. "Lilith? What are you doing here? You have to go, otherwise they'll catch you."
"Just say...", I whispered to myself. While we were trying to loosen the chains around his arms, voices approached and the quiet footsteps became louder and louder. "Quick! Climb back into the chimney and disappear. Don't ever come back. If we see each other again, then not in this city." He spoke quickly and the panic in his eyes didn't exactly help to calm me down. I followed his advice. I couldn't stay any longer. Damn it, Al. After I left the chimney, I ran away. It hurt to lose such a loyal friend. Would I lead him to... the other city? So many things went through my head. I was so angry, but also sad. I had been intensely occupied with the cities outside and with the main city of the infected. It was called Alcatraz, just like the prison. The name fit very well with what I had read about this place. Not to mention that the non-mutated had interrupted all the country's connections that had remained with the infected surroundings. Tragic story.
Resounding quietness surrounded me on the way home. The thoughts in my head were spinning and it bothered me that I hadn't been able to help Al. When I finally arrived home after this terrible walk, I was almost in tears and the thunder in the sky from the clouds above me could scare anyone. My father was already asleep on the sofa. On television, a rerun of a film from about 10-12 years ago was playing. Sighing, I went quietly to my room. I let myself fall into bed. I could barely keep my eyes open and fell asleep almost immediately.
Explosion
January 19, 2543, at 2:34 PM
Time was running out. A few days ago Alborn had been taken away. Where, I didn't know. Only that they had taken him somewhere. The men's faces seemed familiar to me, but I simply couldn't remember where from. Sighing, I placed my hands on the system in front of me, which glowed red and violet - hacking it would be easy for me. I doubted they had even secured it... But I should rather leave that. But naturally, I put aside my moral scruples. My fingers moved as if remote-controlled over the keyboard and made different monitors appear. Damn, I'm good. I was very well known on a few websites, they called me "SPIRIT" there. A name that stands out. I have to admit that I use the name S3P3IERT on every website, but I like the thought that it was given to me by others.
I downloaded the surveillance camera footage to my mobile device and watched every single one. Nothing. As if they had never been there. That doesn't make sense. The cameras are well secured, even against remote access. How...? DAMN IT. I screamed, to chase the thoughts out of my head. I went to the door, put on my shoes and took my keys. "I'll be right back, Dad." Silence. That's normal, he never answered. He was probably busy again with something more important than me.
When I left the apartment, I felt a shiver down my spine that gave me the creeps. Alone. I ignored the feeling and forced myself to go to the pawn shop and do some research. But my legs carried me to Anton's small bar. It was very quiet there and I urgently needed someone to talk to. Who would be better for that than a bartender who still owes you money?
It was unusually full, full of people I had never seen before. Anton usually worked alone and was certainly very stressed because of the many guests. "I'd like a coffee." I deliberately spoke in a low voice to annoy him a little. He turned around briefly and I had to laugh quietly when I saw the relief on his face. "Oh God, Lilith, don't scare me like that..." he said quietly in a tired voice. "You look like you have a lot to do... Should I help you? There's really a lot going on here." I certainly didn't feel like serving these annoying people, but I felt sorry for Anton because he had to cope with the crowd all by himself. "Would you do that? You'll get your money later...", he mumbled and looked at me with his puppy-dog eyes. Advanced war tactics...
After I had changed my clothes into my work uniform, I helped Anton at the bar. Despite his constant attempts to flirt with me, which honestly didn't bother me at all, the work went well. I'll talk to Anton after the shift. I have to get Al out of my head, even though I know that after this shift at the bar I'll continue my research in his pawn shop, but still...
Flames shot out of Thassalin's throat when the gigantic Thraki set fire to a certain piece of wood and then turned around to discover movements. Curiously, the snake behind him fell silent when he came closer. Thassalin had forgotten the passengers on his back.
"That's right, Tenuk, you've already transformed into a Thracian once!"
"If I were to fly myself, that would be completely different from being suddenly lifted up by a gigantic pink dragon!"
"It wasn't that bad, was it, Kayel?"
Kayel apparently wasn't of Nyssi's opinion. He looked out less black than before and his claws had dug so deep into Thassalin's back that the Thracian was bleeding. However, that didn't seem to bother Thassalin. Nevertheless, it had become clear to him that he had scared his new friends, and he collapsed onto a clearing.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I HAD TASTED SOMETHING. THEN I HAD TO TAKE CARE OF IT!"
"But did you also have to drag us along with you?" grumbled Tenuk, as he climbed down from Thassalin's mane and slid down her tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We left our big, strong fighter stuck in the mud! How is he supposed to catch up with us?"
"And he'll probably remember something...", Nyssi mumbled. "Retvik isn't the fastest, but he's not stupid."
"Okay, but is Retvik going by car?"
Nyssi nodded and turned back towards Tenuk. "Of course he can go."
"Have you ever seen Retvik drive a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like you, and I haven't even seen him drive a car as fancy as Kayel's. Besides, he only started taking the car to work because you always threatened us. He only has his bike."
Laughter interrupted them. Thalassin suddenly seemed to find something incredibly amusing, but no one knew what he was laughing about. It lasted a little too long until Thalassin calmed down.
"I'M SORRY, BUT I MISSED YOUR GIANT FRIEND IN ARMOR ON SUCH A CHILDREN'S BIKE FROM TEMTHAN. THAT WAS LAUGHABLE! I WISH I HAD SOME KIND OF TELEPATHY. A GREAT IDEA! ONE I CAN'T LET GO OF."
Kayel sighed, because he could imagine what Thassalin was thinking. "Yes, that's true. But what did you know, and why did you put yourself in danger?"
The dragon roared, flew away and disappeared. When he returned a short while later, he threw something dead at Nyssi's feet. It was an Orothrack, a very rare creature of a pale golden dragon. But it was missing its head. "I LOVE A DEAD ONE. I HEAR THEIR CRIES. TASTE THEIR BLOOD. SOMETHING DRIVES ME TO PROTECT AND TO HUNT. AS YISINI COMMANDS. THEY ARE VERY DESTRUCTIVE."
The Thraki colossus remained completely still and silent. Nyssi and Kayel also remained still and silent and looked attentively towards a clearing in the glade. Something large and black puffed and blew towards them. Whatever it was, it spread out two gigantic pairs of wings and flew towards Thassalin without bothering about the three small creatures among them. Kayel and Tenuk just managed to get to safety, but Nyssi was dragged along with it and almost slammed onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to this attack by grabbing Nyssi and throwing him with his incredibly long and agile tail onto his back, before he himself rose into the air. The black two-winged creature followed them with great speed.
Grit hit Kayel with the club, while he took his rifle from his back and pulled out a bag, which contained a belt with ammunition. He put the belt around his chest, but quickly noticed that Nyssi, the Thracian and the monster were out of sight.
"Hey, Tenuk, can you transform into something that can fly?", asked Kayel.
"Do you want to follow him?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... One of them is a huge monster!"
"Hey, what's up? I'm here with a very qualified rifle in hand and could start shooting right away. But well, how should I say it - I'd have to be able to see him, so that I can hit him."
Tenuk hesitated, then he went back to have more space. With a painful groan, Tenuk's body stretched out, his fur changed into scales and his arm changed into wings. Quickly he transformed into a normal light blue Thraki, but his eyes remained red.
"Come up."
With an appearance like a normal Thracian, Tenuk now had a shield with scales that went along his back. Practically, a few spines had also grown on his back, to which Kayel could hold on. It took a bit too long until Tenuk's take-off was successful, but once in the air, he quickly oriented himself and tried to pursue the others.
Tenuk and Kayel quickly realised that they weren't alone. A second dark creature came like an arrow from bottom to top into the height and Tenuk was barely able to avoid a collision.
"This must be the other gigantic, terrifying monster that Lanex was afraid of?" Kayel frowned. He tried to shoot the second beast, missed, and quickly reloaded.
Tenuk did not answer. He was too busy concentrating on the flight towards Nyssi and Thassalin, even though the other beast was following him. Kayel turned awkwardly to keep the monster in sight. That it was following them was an advantage for Kayel, because that way he could aim and shoot better. Two shots went through the beast's upper wing. It shrieked in pain and fell to the ground under the bush. Kayel was not sure if it was still following him, but it certainly would not have been able to keep up with them.
A good distance away from them, Nyssi held on desperately, while Thassalin flailed around and shot flames at the charred monster. The creature was definitely wounded. It seemed furious, but not ready to give up. The fireballs did not seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin stretched, Nyssi took the opportunity to draw her own weapon, a good old flintlock. It was certainly not the first choice, but perhaps the pellets would cool down the black beast.
No, apparently not. The creature just puffed and tried to fly directly towards Thassalin. Fortunately, Thassalin, despite his size, was mobile enough and dodged, but Nyssi screamed because he had almost lost his grip on Thassalin's smooth scales.
"HOW CAN WE CATCH HIM?", Nyssi called.
"LOOK AT THEIR HEADS!"
"THAT'S GOING TO BE DIFFICULT!"
Thassalin whistled and then drew a tighter circle around the mountain, which he called his home. The dark beast followed, but panicked slightly when a thread of fire touched it from behind. It hadn't noticed that it was no longer alone. It panicked even more when Thassalin slowed down and then lashed his tail against its head, driving it off its path.
Swearing and grumbling, she flew up and spat into the air. Then everything turned dark, as if the monster had sucked the light out of the sky and replaced it with a cloud of eternal night.
When he suddenly saw nothing more, Thassalin tried to retreat. He noticed how he was scratched by the branches, before he finally fell into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen and shot directly towards him, dragging the black cloud with it.
"Kayel!", shouted Tenuk, when he flew out of a cloud and began to circle, to keep watch in the darkness below for Nyssi and Thassalin. "What are we going to do now? Kayel...? Kayel, where are you?"
Below, Nyssi got to her feet with difficulty. She was sure she had broken something, but her particular supernatural healing powers had already begun to take effect. Unfortunately, this did not apply to Thassalin. He leaned, dead tired, against the only tree that had not collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made every effort to get close to Thassalin, but she could barely see two meters away. Everything was like a dark night and wounded in solitary shadows. And in this shadow, something rustled and stirred.
A terrifying tail full of armor slammed down next to Nyssi on the ground and made her fall over. However, she noticed that the tail was just thrashing wildly and not intentionally trying to touch her. The beast, or what little Nyssi saw or heard of it, grinned and clawed at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, pierced the monster, and confused it.
All at once a gunshot echoed through the air and the monster fell silent, collapsed to the ground and lay motionless. The darkness around them dissolved and they saw what had happened: on the beast stood Kayel, holding his rifle firmly and smoking.
"That must have been... the stupidest shadow jump I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...", Kabel had trouble breathing. His eyes glowed almost black and a dark energy surrounded his body like a snake. But even as he spoke, the color returned to his armor and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment until Nyssi understood what had happened. They all knew that Kayel possessed these singular shadow powers. He only used them rarely, because to many they seemed very strange and truly frightening. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel was able to infuse these powers into any kind of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he seemed to be quite surprised himself.
"Is everything all right with you?", Nyssi asked.
"Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, and I'm just fine again." Kayel contemplated his work while Tenuk flew down, landed next to him and took on his usual form of Spast again.
Now, when the beast no longer moved, she could see better what it was. Its fur was black as coal and slimy, but the slime remained firmly attached to its body. It had four wings and four extremities, all of which ended in narrow, long claws, and two smooth horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the devil they had in front of them, something turned and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't reach them, because a familiar vehicle crashed into its flank and ensured that the monster slid dead in front of Nyssi's feet. Nyssi didn't want to risk anything. She grabbed her rifle, shot a bullet into its head without hesitation, and the creature died on the spot.
"Oops.." Retvik mumbled from the driver's seat before he clumsily turned off the engine and got out of the truck. "Um, that wasn't really intentional. Is everything alright with you?"
"You missed all the action," Tenuk grumbled. "Where were you?"
"You all just left me alone. I came as fast as possible...", Retvik sighed. "May I ask what kind of horrible beasts those are?"
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had sat up again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit confused, but not too badly injured.
"YOU HAVE KILLED THE CORRUPTED! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. CREATURES THAT HAD GONE FROM HERE WHEN CORRUPTION HAD ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
"You mean the horrible monster-creature of God, that we... helped to kill?" Tenuk mumbled.
"YES, EXACTLY THAT. PERHAPS THERE'S MORE. BUT I COULDN'T SHOOT HIM IN THE HEAD. I DON'T HAVE A FIREARM. AND TWO AGAINST ONE ISN'T FAIR, IS IT?" Thassalin limped towards Kayel and stroked his head. "THANK YOU VERY MUCH, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT AS BLOODTHIRSTY AND NOT AS CAPABLE OF KILLING ENTIRE UNIVERSES."
"Um... thanks... I think...", Kayel shrugged. "So, are we done here then?"
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She took out her camera and took a few photos of the beasts that were now definitely dead. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the decorated dagger of the god of the dead, and began to saw off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards she started with the second one. But just as Nyssi was about to finish, the beasts suddenly went up in flames and transformed into a pile of ashes within seconds. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
"Well, this is now practical and impractical at the same time...", Nyssi sighed. "But at least I have the photos, I hope."
